        "@type":"Question",
        "name":"When did the CBAM definitive regime start?",
        "acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The definitive CBAM regime started on 1 January 2026. From that date, importers of CBAM goods above the applicable threshold need to move beyond transitional reporting and prepare for authorisation, annual emissions declarations and certificate surrender obligations."}
      },
      {
        "@type":"Question",
        "name":"Is aluminium covered by CBAM?",
        "acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes. Aluminium has been one of the covered sectors since the transitional phase and remains covered in the definitive regime. The scope includes unwrought aluminium under CN 7601 and a wider list of aluminium product CN codes, while aluminium scrap under CN 7602 00 and certain household articles under CN 7615 are excluded in the European Commission guidance."}
      },
      {
        "@type":"Question",
        "name":"Who needs authorised CBAM declarant status?",
        "acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"EU importers, or their indirect customs representatives, importing more than the 50-tonne mass threshold of CBAM goods into the EU need to apply for authorised CBAM declarant status. The European Commission urges importers to apply as soon as possible, and national authorities such as DEHSt advise applying well in advance of exceeding the threshold."}
      },
      {
        "@type":"Question",
        "name":"What data does the non-EU supplier need to provide?",
        "acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The supplier needs to provide quantity by good and installation, direct embedded emissions, relevant indirect emissions, production route information, precursor information where relevant, and any carbon price already paid in the country of origin. For aluminium, the Commission guidance also points to sector-specific details such as tonnes of scrap used and alloy content percentage."}
      },
      {
        "@type":"Question",
        "name":"Can carbon costs already paid outside the EU be deducted?",
        "acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes. The European Commission states that if the importer can prove a carbon price has already been paid during production in the country of origin, the corresponding amount can be deducted from the CBAM obligation."}
      }
    ]
  }
